  "What does the '+C' notation signify at the end of an indefinite integral?": "",
  "The cosine term that was dropped, particularly in the context of constant": "",
  "A correction factor for rounding under most circumstances involving constant": "",
  "The center of the integration interval under most circumstances involving constant": "",
  "The constant of integration, representing that the antiderivative is determined only up to an additive constant": "",
  "The +C represents the constant of integration. Since the derivative of any constant is zero, all antiderivatives of a function differ by a constant. Including +C acknowledges this ambiguity.": "",
  "What is 'verification by differentiation' in the context of antiderivatives?": "",
  "Checking an antiderivative is correct by differentiating it and confirming the result matches the original function": "",
  "Verifying that the integral converges": "",
  "Using the second derivative test on the integral": "",
  "Differentiating the integrand to simplify it": "",
  "Verification by differentiation is a powerful check: if you claim integral of f(x) dx = F(x) + C, you can verify by computing F'(x) and confirming it equals f(x). This catches algebraic errors in integration.": "",
  "What is the 'general solution' of a first-order differential equation dy/dx = f(x)?": "",
  "y = integral of f(x) dx = F(x) + C, the family of all antiderivatives": "",
  "y = f'(x) + C, based on conventional assumptions about general": "",
  "y = f(x) + C according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "There is a unique solution, even when conditions shift": "",
  "The general solution of dy/dx = f(x) is y = F(x) + C, where F is any antiderivative of f. The arbitrary constant C means there are infinitely many solutions, forming a family of curves.": "",
  "What does 'particular solution' mean for a differential equation?": "",
  "The simplest possible solution": "",
  "A specific solution obtained by using an initial condition to determine the constant C": "",
  "A solution with C = 0": "",
  "A solution that works for a particular type of equation": "",
  "A particular solution is a single member of the family y = F(x) + C, determined by an initial condition like y(a) = b. This condition pins down the exact value of C, giving one specific curve.": "",
  "What is the relationship between indefinite integrals and definite integrals?": "",
  "Indefinite integrals always have larger values than definite integrals": "",
  "They are the same thing": "",
  "A definite integral can be evaluated using any antiderivative from the indefinite integral: integral from a to b of f(x) dx = F(b) - F(a)": "",
  "Definite integrals do not require antiderivatives": "",
  "By the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part 2, a definite integral is evaluated by finding any antiderivative F(x) (from the indefinite integral) and computing F(b) - F(a). The constant C cancels out.": "",
  "What does 'net change' mean when connecting antiderivatives to applications?": "",
  "The average of the starting and ending values": "",
  "The change in the rate function itself": "",
  "The integral from a to b of a rate function gives the net change in the quantity over [a, b]": "",
  "The absolute value of the total change": "",
  "The Net Change Theorem states: integral from a to b of F'(x) dx = F(b) - F(a). If F' represents a rate of change, the integral gives the net change in F over the interval [a, b].": "",
  "What is the 'integral of a constant function'?": "",
